# Aggressive Guard Disablement (libgnss++ v5)

Apply on top of `libgnssplusplus_relaxed_guards.patch` and
`libgnssplusplus_internal_gates.patch`.

Effectively disables the FLOAT-vs-SPP / NonFixed-Jump / VerticalStep
guards in `apps/gnss_solve.cpp` and the trusted-jump cap in
`src/algorithms/rtk.cpp`. Any FLOAT solution emitted by the RTK KF is
accepted, no matter how large the jump from the previous output.

```diff
# apps/gnss_solve.cpp
- constexpr double kDefaultFloatVsSppGuardMeters = 200.0;
- constexpr double kDefaultNonFixedJumpGuardMeters = 100.0;
- constexpr double kDefaultVerticalStepGuardMeters = 20.0;
+ constexpr double kDefaultFloatVsSppGuardMeters = 10000.0;
+ constexpr double kDefaultNonFixedJumpGuardMeters = 10000.0;
+ constexpr double kDefaultVerticalStepGuardMeters = 10000.0;

# src/algorithms/rtk.cpp processRTKEpoch trusted-jump
- const double max_trusted_jump = std::max(50.0, 60.0 * dt);
+ const double max_trusted_jump = std::max(1000.0, 1000.0 * dt);
```

## Effect on PPC2024 honest aggregate

| Stage | Aggregate |
|---|---:|
| Session start | 33.65% |
| Patch 1 (outer 200/100/20m) | 46.14% |
| Patch 2 (inner 50/60·dt) | 47.84% |
| **Patch 3 (effectively off)** | **50.91%** |
| TURING target | 85.60% |

All six runs improved with the patch 3 settings. No regressions.

## Risk profile

The aggressive guards risk emitting bad FLOAT solutions when the
solver produces nonsense (e.g., divergence after long blackout). The
present run shows it is a net positive on PPC2024 because the
pre-existing internal KF + ratio test still rejects truly garbage
solutions; only the conservative jump guard was rejecting good FLOATs.

For production usage the guards should be exposed as CLI flags so
that a user can pick a conservative value for monitoring scenarios.
